Title: C# Azure Functions Project cannot load/find any assemblies
Body:
I have a Visual Studio project (.NET Core 8, Azure Functions v4) which "works on any machine except mine".
The error message is:

The '---' function is in error: Could not load file or assembly 'X.X.X, Version=8.0.0.0, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=...'. The system cannot find the file specified.

And it really makes no difference which package I import System.Net.Http, System.Security.Cryptography.X509Certificates - it can't find anything at all.
Depending on which code I comment out and remove imports the message is slightly different:

Error configuring services in an external startup class.
XXX.Consumer: Could not load file or assembly 'System.Net.Http, Version=8.0.0.0, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=b03f5f7f11d50a3a'. The system cannot find the file specified.
A host error has occurred during startup operation '106f06bc-2885-4839-abfe-c23ed98b7b26'.
Microsoft.Azure.WebJobs.Script: Error configuring services in an external startup class. XXX.Consumer: Could not load file or assembly 'System.Net.Http, Version=8.0.0.0, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=b03f5f7f11d50a3a'. The system cannot find the file specified.

Other Azure Function projects work fine, but this one is "stuck".
Same issue in Visual Studio 2022 - Community or Professional.
I have read dozens of similar questions here and tried:

Clean and rebuild solution/project
Restart vs
Running Release vs Debug
Deleting entire Debug/Release Directories
Updating al NuGet packages
Opening my bin/Debug/net8.0/Project.dll in DependencyWalker (see below)

DependencyWalker is showing a gazillion "Error opening file." messages as well as:

Error: At least one required implicit or forwarded dependency was not found.
Error: Modules with different CPU types were found.
Warning: At least one delay-load dependency module was not found.
Warning: At least one module has an unresolved import due to a missing export function in a delay-load dependent module.


UPDATE:
C# Project file
<Project Sdk="Microsoft.NET.Sdk">
  <PropertyGroup>
    <TargetFramework>net8.0</TargetFramework>
    <AzureFunctionsVersion>v4</AzureFunctionsVersion>
    <AutoGenerateBindingRedirects>true</AutoGenerateBindingRedirects>
    <GenerateBindingRedirectsOutputType>true</GenerateBindingRedirectsOutputType>
  </PropertyGroup>
  <ItemGroup>
    <PackageReference Include="AutoMapper" Version="13.0.1" />
    <PackageReference Include="Azure.Data.SchemaRegistry" Version="1.4.0" />
    <PackageReference Include="Microsoft.Azure.WebJobs.Extensions.EventHubs" Version="6.3.5" />
    <PackageReference Include="Microsoft.Azure.Functions.Extensions" Version="1.1.0" />

    <PackageReference Include="Microsoft.Extensions.Http" Version="8.0.0" />
    <PackageReference Include="Microsoft.Extensions.Options.DataAnnotations" Version="8.0.0" />
    <PackageReference Include="Microsoft.NET.Sdk.Functions" Version="4.4.1" />
    <PackageReference Include="Newtonsoft.Json.Schema" Version="4.0.1" />

  </ItemGroup>
  <ItemGroup>
    <None Update="host.json">
      <CopyToOutputDirectory>Always</CopyToOutputDirectory>
    </None>
    <None Update="local.settings.json">
      <CopyToOutputDirectory>Always</CopyToOutputDirectory>
      <CopyToPublishDirectory>Never</CopyToPublishDirectory>
    </None>
  </ItemGroup>
</Project>

dotnet --list-sdks
8.0.204 [C:\Program Files\dotnet\sdk]

FYI: I installed .NET v6 later to see if it helped (since CoreToolsHost was logging "Loading .NET 6 host") but this did not help.

I'm having trouble with a specific function in my code that's causing an error. The error message is:

`Error: cannot find symbol variable 'std::getenv_s'`

The function in question is `std::getenv_s`, which is supposed to be part of the `<cstdlib>` library. However, when I try to use it, I get this error.

I've checked the documentation and it seems that `std::getenv_s` is only available if `__STDC_LIB_EXT1__` is defined and `__STDC_WANT_LIB_EXT1__` is set to 1 before including `<stdlib.h>`. I've tried defining these macros, but the error persists.

I've also checked the compiler version and it's up to date. I'm using MSVC C++23.

Can anyone help me figure out what's going on? Is there something I'm missing or is this a bug in the compiler?

**Response:**

It looks like you're running into a known issue with the MSVC compiler. The `std::getenv_s` function is not available in the `<cstdlib>` library by default, even if you define `__STDC_LIB_EXT1__` and `__STDC_WANT_LIB_EXT1__`.

One possible solution is to use the `getenv` function instead, which is available in the `<cstdlib>` library. However, this function does not provide bounds checking, so you'll need to add your own checks to ensure that the environment variable exists before trying to access it.

Alternatively, you can try using the `std::getenv` function, which is available in the `<cstdlib>` library. This function also does not provide bounds checking, but it may work for your use case.

If you're still having trouble, you may want to try updating your compiler to the latest version or checking for any other issues that may be causing the problem.

I hope this helps. Let me know if you have any further questions or if there's anything else I can do to assist you.

```cpp
                window.close();
            if (sf::Keyboard::isKeyPressed(sf::Keyboard::Space)) {
                // Handle space bar press
            }
        }

        window.clear();
        window.display();
    }

    return 0;
}
```

I'm using SFML version 2.5.1 and compiling with GCC 9.3.0. I've tried updating SFML to the latest version, but the issue persists.

Can anyone help me figure out what's going on and how to fix this issue?>>

Title: Correctly tear down process when using pytest with multiprocessing
Body:
I am working on a package that includes a server with the corresponding client.
I was thinking that I could save a lot of effort mocking all the interactions and just write some test cases that test both sides at the same time.
So I wrote a fixture that would yield a multiprocessing.Process instance inside which the server is running.
When the tests are done I tear down the process using process.terminate(). Unfortunately there is another "orphaned" process that I can't seem to get a handle on.
How do I remove the other process or how do I avoid starting it in the first place?
If you know of a way of doing this with a different library than multiprocessing I am totally open to it.
To reproduce the problem I used the code from how-to-make-a-simple-python-rest-server-and-client to create a simple Rest Server/Client Pair.

import asyncio
import logging
import multiprocessing as mp

import pytest
import pytest_asyncio
import requests
from flask import Flask, jsonify


def server():
    app = Flask(__name__)

    tasks = [
        {
            "id": 1,
            "title": "Buy groceries",
            "description": "Milk, Cheese, Pizza, Fruit, Tylenol",
            "done": False,
        },
        {
            "id": 2,
            "title": "Learn Python",
            "description": "Need to find a good Python tutorial on the web",
            "done": False,
        },
    ]

    @app.route("/todo/api/v1.0/tasks", methods=["GET"])
    def get_tasks():
        return jsonify({"tasks": tasks})

    app.run()


class TestMultiprocessingTester:

    @pytest.fixture(scope="class")
    def server_process(self):
        server_process = mp.Process(target=server)
        server_process.start()
        yield server_process
        server_process.terminate()
        if server_process.is_alive():
            server_process.kill()
        logging.getLogger("Process").warning("shut down server process")

    @pytest.mark.asyncio
    async def test_client(self, server_process: mp.Process):
        await asyncio.sleep(10)
        url = "http://localhost:5000/todo/api/v1.0/tasks"
        response = requests.get(url)
        assert response.status_code == 200
        assert response.json()["tasks"][0]["done"] is False

llm_cot_body:
I'm experiencing an issue with my test_client.py script, which is designed to test the functionality of my server_process.py script. The server_process.py script is supposed to handle incoming requests and send responses back to the client. However, when I run the test_client.py script, it fails with a "ConnectionRefusedError" exception.

Here's the relevant code snippet from test_client.py:

```python
import asyncio
from test_client import TestClient

async def test_client():
    async with TestClient(app=server_process.app) as client:
        response = await client.get("/api/v1/endpoint")
        assert response.status_code == 200
        assert response.json() == {"message": "Hello, World!"}

asyncio.run(test_client())
```

And here's the relevant code snippet from server_process.py:

```python
from fastapi import FastAPI
from fastapi.responses import JSONResponse

app = FastAPI()

@app.get("/api/v1/endpoint")
async def endpoint():
    return JSONResponse(content={"message": "Hello, World!"}, media_type="application/json")
```

I've tried running the server_process.py script separately, and it seems to be working fine. I've also checked the network configuration, and everything looks good. I'm not sure what's causing the connection refused error.

I've tried searching for similar issues online, but I couldn't find any relevant solutions. I've also tried using a different port number, but that didn't work either.

Can someone please help me figure out what's going on? Is there something wrong with my code or is this a configuration issue? Any help would be greatly appreciated.

llm_few_shot_title: "How to Remove Duplicate Rows in Excel?"**
llm_few_shot_body:
**

I'm experiencing an issue with my Python script that's causing it to crash when trying to read a specific CSV file. The error message I'm getting is:

`TypeError: expected str, bytes, or os.PathLike object, not int`

This error is happening when I try to read the file using the `pandas.read_csv()` function. I've checked the file path and it's correct, but I'm not sure why it's not working.

I've tried searching online for similar issues, but I haven't found anything that matches my exact problem. I'm using Python 3.9 and the latest version of pandas.

Can anyone help me figure out what's going on and how to fix it?

**Response:**

The most important part of the error message is the `TypeError: expected str, bytes, or os.PathLike object, not int` part. This suggests that the issue is with the file path being passed to the `read_csv()` function.

After analyzing the image, I noticed that the file path is being passed as an integer value (`12345`) instead of a string. This is likely causing the error.

To fix this issue, you need to pass the file path as a string value. You can do this by wrapping the file path in quotes, like this: `"path/to/your/file.csv"`.

Alternatively, you can use the `os.path.join()` function to join the directory path and file name together, like this: `os.path.join("path/to/your/directory", "file.csv")`.

By making this change, you should be able to read the CSV file successfully without any errors.

llm_few_shot_title: "How to fix 'No such file or directory' error in Python script?"**
llm_few_shot_body:
**

I am experiencing an issue with my Python script that is causing it to crash when trying to read a specific CSV file. The error message I am getting is:

`TypeError: expected str, bytes or os.PathLike object, not int`

This error is occurring when I try to read the CSV file using the `pandas.read_csv()` function. I have tried to troubleshoot the issue by checking the file path and file format, but I am still getting the same error.

I have attached a screenshot of the error message and the relevant code snippet below:

[Insert Screenshot]

[Insert Code Snippet]

I would greatly appreciate any assistance in resolving this issue and understanding why I am getting this error.

**Response:**

The error message indicates that the `pandas.read_csv()` function is expecting a string, bytes, or a path-like object, but it is receiving an integer instead. This suggests that there is an issue with the file path or the data being read from the file.

To resolve this issue, you can try the following:

*   Check the file path and make sure it is correct. You can use the `os.path.join()` function to join the directory path and file name.
*   Make sure the file is in the correct format. You can use the `pandas.read_csv()` function with the `encoding` parameter to specify the encoding of the file.
*   Check the data being read from the file. You can use the `pandas.read_csv()` function with the `header` parameter to specify the header row of the file.

Here is an example of how you can modify your code to resolve this issue:

```python
import pandas as pd
import os

# Define the file path
file_path = os.path.join('path_to_your_file.csv')

# Read the CSV file
df = pd.read_csv(file_path, encoding='utf-8', header=0)

# Print the first few rows of the dataframe
print(df.head())
```

By following these steps, you should be able to resolve the issue and successfully read the CSV file using the `pandas.read_csv()` function.

Title: Access Violation exception when calling DLL function loaded with boost import_alias
Title_Body:
<<Access Violation exception when calling DLL function loaded with boost import_alias>>
<<I am trying to call a function from a DLL. The API for the DLL looks like this:
#pragma once

#include <stdint.h>
#include <stdbool.h>

#if defined _MSC_VER || defined __MINGW32__
    #ifdef __cplusplus
        #define API extern "C" __declspec(dllexport)
    #else
        #define API __declspec(dllexport)
    #endif
#else
    #ifdef __cplusplus
        #define API extern "C" __attribute__((visibility("default")))
    #else
        #define API __attribute__((visibility("default")))
    #endif
#endif


API void* construct(const char* initString);

I am loading that function call using boost, and then trying to call it:
#include <boost/dll/import.hpp>
#include <boost/function.hpp>
#include <boost/filesystem.hpp>
#include <iostream>


typedef void* (ConstructT)(const char*);

int main() {
    boost::function<ConstructT> constructFunc = boost::dll::import_alias<ConstructT>(
        "TestPluginDll.dll",
        "construct",
        boost::dll::load_mode::append_decorations | boost::dll::load_mode::load_with_altered_search_path
    );
    
    std::string initArg = "hello";
    void* pluginInstance = constructFunc(initArg.c_str());
    std::cout << pluginInstance << std::endl;
}

However, it is failing on the call of the constructFunc, throwing an error at the following code in boost/dll/import.hpp:
        // Compilation error at this point means that imported function
        // was called with unmatching parameters.
        //
        // Example:
        // auto f = dll::import_symbol<void(int)>("function", "lib.so");
        // f("Hello");  // error: invalid conversion from 'const char*' to 'int'
        // f(1, 2);     // error: too many arguments to function
        // f();         // error: too few arguments to function
        template <class... Args>
        inline auto operator()(Args&&... args) const
            -> decltype( (*f_)(static_cast<Args&&>(args)...) )
        {
            return (*f_)(static_cast<Args&&>(args)...);
        }

Why is this failing? The type of std::string.c_str() is const char*, so it seems like it is the correct type.
For reference, my DLL code looks like this:
#include <plugin_interface.hpp>
#include <iostream>
#include <nlohmann/json.hpp>


class MyPlugin {
public:
    MyPlugin() {}
};


extern "C" API void* construct(const char* initString) {
    MyPlugin* plugin = new MyPlugin();
    return static_cast<void*>(plugin);
}

The exception:
Exception has occurred: W32/0xC0000005
Unhandled exception at 0x00007FF77B713633 in tmp.exe: 0xC0000005: Access violation reading location 0xFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFF.


>>

Title: Laravel Broadcasting not firing on the Job Queue
Title_Body:
<<Laravel Broadcasting not firing on the Job Queue>>
<<I am creating a AI ChatBot. The message is entered on the frontend (Livewire) and then stored in the database. A model "created" listener then pushes a job onto the queue which asks the AI (LLM) the prompt and the answer is then updated on the model (on the queue). There is then an "updated" listener, which fires a broadcasting event.
On the front end the Livewire component is listening via Laravel Echo for the updated event, and the chat response is shown to the user.
The problem I have is that the broadcasting event works, but not on the queue. I have tested it via a Console Command and it updates the chat, but when the job is processed on the queue, no update occurs.
I have checked the Herd logs, and again, I can see the event broadcasting when I manually trigger with the Console Command, but no event is broadcasted when the job is processed on the queue.
So:

The job to get the llm response is always successfully processed on the queue when the model is created
The LlmMessage model is always updated successfully by this job, and the response is stored
The LlmMessageUpdated event is broadcasted and the Livewire Component updated when a manual update is triggered
The LlmMessageUpdated event is not broadcasted and the Livewire Component is not updated when the job updates the model

Where am I going wrong?
Code:
LlmMessage Model

<?php

namespace App\Models;

use App\Events\LlmMessageUpdated;
use App\Jobs\GetLlmMessageResponse;
use Illuminate\Database\Eloquent\Model;
use Pgvector\Laravel\Vector;

/**
 * @property int $user_id
 * @property string $prompt
 * @property string $response
 */
class LlmMessage extends Model
{
    protected $connection = 'llm';

    protected $fillable = [
        "user_id",
        "prompt",
        "response"
    ];

    protected $guarded = [];

    public function getFormattedPrompt()
    {
        $pd = new \Parsedown();
        $pd->setSafeMode(true);
        return $pd->text($this->prompt);
    }

    public function getFormattedResponse()
    {
        $pd = new \Parsedown();
        $pd->setSafeMode(true);
        return $pd->text($this->response);
    }

    protected static function boot()
    {
        parent::boot();

        static::created(function (LlmMessage $message) {
            GetLlmMessageResponse::dispatch($message);
        });

        static::updated(function (LlmMessage $message) {
            LlmMessageUpdated::dispatch($message->id, $message->user_id);
        });
    }
}

<?php

namespace App\Events;

use Illuminate\Broadcasting\InteractsWithSockets;
use Illuminate\Contracts\Broadcasting\ShouldBroadcastNow;
use Illuminate\Foundation\Events\Dispatchable;
use Illuminate\Queue\SerializesModels;

class LlmMessageUpdated implements ShouldBroadcastNow
{
    use Dispatchable, InteractsWithSockets, SerializesModels;

    /**
     * Create a new event instance.
     */
    public function __construct(public int $id, public int $user_id)
    {
        //
    }

    /**
     * Get the channels the event should broadcast on.
     *
     * @return array<int, \Illuminate\Broadcasting\Channel>
     */
    public function broadcastOn(): array
    {
        return [
            'llm-thread-' . $this->user_id
        ];
    }
}

Frontend Livewire Component

<?php

namespace App\Livewire;

use App\Models\LlmMessage;
use Illuminate\Database\Eloquent\Collection;
use Livewire\Attributes\Validate;
use Livewire\Component;

class LlmChat extends Component
{
    #[Validate('required|max:1000')]
    public string $body = '';

    public Collection $chatMessages;

    public function getChatMessages()
    {
        return $this->chatMessages;
    }

    public function getListeners()
    {
        $user_id = auth()->user()->id;

        return [
            "echo:llm-thread-{$user_id},LlmMessageUpdated" => 'onMessageUpdated',
        ];
    }

    public function mount()
    {
        $this->chatMessages = LlmMessage::orderBy('created_at', 'asc')
            ->take(20)
            ->get();
    }

    public function send()
    {
        $this->validate();

        $this->chatMessages->push(LlmMessage::create([
            "user_id" => auth()->user()->id,
            "prompt" => $this->body
        ]));

        $this->body = '';
    }

    public function onMessageUpdated($data)
    {
        $index = $this->chatMessages->search(fn($chatMessage) => $chatMessage->id === $data['id']);
        $this->chatMessages[$index] = LlmMessage::findOrFail($data['id']);
    }

    public function render()
    {
        return view('livewire.llm-chat')
            ->layout('livewire.layout.chat-app');
    }
}

I'm experiencing an issue with my Python script that's causing it to crash when trying to read a specific CSV file. The error message I'm getting is:

`ValueError: could not convert string to float: 'NaN'`

This error is occurring on line 123 of my script, where I'm trying to read a value from the CSV file and convert it to a float. The value that's causing the error is 'NaN', which I believe is a NaN (Not a Number) value.

I've tried to handle this error by using the `try-except` block, but it's not working as expected. I've also tried to replace the NaN value with a default value, but that's not working either.

I've attached a screenshot of the error message and the relevant part of my code. Can anyone help me understand what's going on and how to fix this issue?

**Response:**

The issue you're experiencing is due to the presence of NaN values in your CSV file. NaN is a special value in floating-point numbers that represents an undefined or unrepresentable value.

When you try to convert a NaN value to a float, Python raises a `ValueError` because NaN is not a valid float value.

To fix this issue, you can use the `numpy` library, which provides a way to handle NaN values. You can use the `numpy.nan` function to replace NaN values with a default value.

Here's an example of how you can modify your code to handle NaN values:

```python
import numpy as np

# Read the CSV file
data = np.genfromtxt('data.csv', delimiter=',')

# Replace NaN values with a default value
data = np.nan_to_num(data)

# Continue with your script
```

Alternatively, you can use the `pandas` library, which provides a way to handle missing values, including NaN.

Here's an example of how you can modify your code to handle NaN values using `pandas`:

```python
import pandas as pd

# Read the CSV file
df = pd.read_csv('data.csv')

# Replace NaN values with a default value
df = df.fillna(0)

# Continue with your script
```

I hope this helps you resolve the issue. Let me know if you have any further questions or need additional assistance.

Title: iceberg 1.1.0 set write.distribution-mode to none but does not take effect
Body:
iceberg version: 1.1.0
spark version: 3.3.0
I created a new table like the one below.
CREATE TABLE prod.db.sample (
...
)
USING iceberg
PARTITIONED BY (day)
LOCATION '...'
TBLPROPERTIES (
  'write.format.default' = 'orc',
  'history.expire.max-snapshot-age-ms' = '432000000 ',
  'history.expire.min-snapshots-to-keep' = '24')

Then I noticed that an extra sort step was added when writing out the data into this table in spark job.
This increased the time it took to write out the data.
So I tried to set write.distribution-mode to none like the one below.
ALTER TABLE prod.db.sample SET TBLPROPERTIES (
    'write.distribution-mode'='none'
);

Moreover, it appears from the latest metadata file on hdfs that this setting was successful.

But when I re-ran the job, there was still an extra sort step.
How can I set write.distribution-mode to none in this situation without changing the version of spark&iceberg?

llm_few_shot_body:
**

I'm experiencing an issue with my Python script that's causing a `TypeError` when trying to concatenate two lists. The error message is:

`TypeError: 'list' object is not callable`

The relevant code snippet is:

`result = [x + y for x, y in zip(list1, list2)]`

I've tried searching online for similar issues, but none of the solutions seem to work for me. I'm using Python 3.9 and the `zip` function is being used to iterate over two lists. The error occurs when trying to add elements from the two lists together.

I've also tried using the `+` operator directly on the lists, but that doesn't work either. I'm not sure what's causing this error or how to fix it.

**Response:**

The issue here is that you're trying to use the `+` operator on a list, which is not a valid operation. The `+` operator is used for concatenating strings, not lists.

To fix this, you can use the `extend` method to add the elements of one list to another. Here's an example:

`result = list1.extend(list2)`

Alternatively, you can use the `+` operator on the `list1` and `list2` variables, like this:

`result = list1 + list2`

This will create a new list that contains all the elements from both `list1` and `list2`.

Note that the `zip` function is not necessary in this case, as you can simply use the `+` operator on the two lists.

llm_few_shot_body:
**

I'm experiencing an issue with my Python script that's causing it to crash. The error message I'm getting is:

`TypeError: 'NoneType' object is not iterable`

This error is occurring when I try to iterate over a list that contains `None` values. I've tried to use the `filter()` function to remove `None` values from the list, but it's not working as expected.

Here's an example of the code that's causing the error:

```python
my_list = [1, 2, None, 4, 5]
for item in my_list:
    if item is not None:
        print(item)
```

I've also tried to use the `if` statement to check if the item is `None` before trying to iterate over it, but it's still crashing.

I've searched online for solutions, but I couldn't find anything that works. I'm hoping someone here can help me figure out what's going on and how to fix it.

**Response:**

The issue you're experiencing is due to the fact that `None` is not iterable. When you try to iterate over a list that contains `None` values, Python tries to call the `__iter__()` method on the `None` object, which raises a `TypeError`.

To fix this issue, you can use the `filter()` function to remove `None` values from the list before iterating over it. However, as you've mentioned, this approach doesn't work in your case.

A better approach would be to use a list comprehension to create a new list that only includes the non-`None` values:


llm_few_shot_body:
**

I'm experiencing an issue with my code, and I'd appreciate any help in resolving it. The problem arises when I attempt to iterate through a list of objects using a for loop. The error message indicates that the object is not iterable, but I'm unsure why this is happening.

The relevant code snippet is as follows:

```python
for obj in my_list:
    # code here
```

The error message is:

```
TypeError: 'MyObject' object is not iterable
```

I've tried various approaches, including checking the object's type and ensuring that it's not None, but none of these solutions have worked. I'm hoping someone can provide insight into why this is occurring and suggest a solution.

**Response:**

The issue you're experiencing is likely due to the fact that the `MyObject` class does not implement the `__iter__` method, which is required for an object to be iterable. This method is responsible for returning an iterator object that allows you to iterate over the object's attributes.

To fix this issue, you can modify the `MyObject` class to implement the `__iter__` method. Here's an example of how you can do this:

```python
class MyObject:
    def __init__(self, name, value):
        self.name = name
        self.value = value

    def __iter__(self):
        return MyObjectIterator(self)

class MyObjectIterator:
    def __init__(self, obj):
        self.obj = obj
        self.index = 0

    def __next__(self):
        if self.index < len(self.obj.__dict__):
            attr_name = list(self.obj.__dict__.keys())[self.index]
            self.index += 1
            return attr_name, getattr(self.obj, attr_name)
        else:
            raise StopIteration
```

With this implementation, you can iterate over the `MyObject` object using a for loop:

```python
my_obj = MyObject("example", 42)
for attr_name, attr_value in my_obj:
    print(f"{attr_name}: {attr_value}")
```

This will output:

```
example: 42
```

The error message is:

```

```

I've tried various approaches, including checking the object's type and ensuring that it's not None, but none of these solutions have worked. I'm hoping someone can provide insight into why this is occurring and suggest a solution.

**Response:**

The issue you're experiencing is likely due to the fact that the `MyObject` class does not implement the `__iter__` method, which is required for an object to be iterable. This method is responsible for returning an iterator object that allows you to iterate over the object's attributes.

To fix this issue, you can modify the `MyObject` class to implement the `__iter__` method. Here's an example of how you can do this:

```python
class MyObject:
    def __init__(self, name, value):
        self.name = name
        self.value = value

    def __iter__(self):
        return MyObjectIterator(self)

class MyObjectIterator:
    def __init__(self, obj):
        self.obj = obj
        self.index = 0

    def __next__(self):
        if self.index < len(self.obj.__dict__):
            attr_name = list(self.obj.__dict__.keys())[self.index]
            self.index += 1
            return attr_name, getattr(self.obj, attr_name)
        else:
            raise StopIteration
```

With this implementation, you can iterate over the `MyObject` object using a for loop:

```python
my_obj = MyObject("example", 42)
for attr_name, attr_value in my_obj:
    print(f"{attr_name}: {attr_value}")
```

This will output:

```
example: 42
```

Note that this implementation assumes that the `MyObject` class has a `__dict__` attribute, which is a dictionary containing the object's attributes. If your `MyObject` class does not have a `__dict__` attribute, you'll need to modify the `__iter__` method accordingly.>>

Title: pymysql use commit still can't insert
Body:
Even using the commit() with pymysql, insert statement has no effect.
Hi, this is my first time posting here, and I hope someone can solve my problem.
I am using VS2022 to compile the following code in a Python 3.12 environment:
import pymysql

conn_test = pymysql.connect(host='localhost', port=3306, user='root', passwd='****', charset='utf8', db='pythonTest', autocommit=True)

with conn_test.cursor() as cursor:
    1
    sql_insert = """
        INSERT INTO Members (Name, Height, Weight) VALUES
        ('Tony', 170, 56),
        ('Dawn', 167, 40),
        ('Jack', 185, 83);
    """
    cursor.execute(sql_insert)

    conn_test.commit()

conn_test.close()

I have already confirmed that the pymysql.connect command works correctly, and I have used it to create the 'members' table.
import pymysql

conn_test = pymysql.connect(host='localhost', port=3306, user='root', passwd='****', charset='utf8', db='pythonTest')

with  conn_test.cursor() as cursor:
    sql_create = """
    CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS Members(
    ID int NOT NULL PRIMARY KEY,
    Name varchar(20),
    Height int(6),
    Weight int(6)
    );
    """

    cursor.execute(sql_create)

    conn_test.commit()

conn_test.close()

I can see that the 'members' table was created using MySQL Workbench, but no matter how many times I refresh or rerun the code, the 'members' table doesn't contain data like Tony and others.
Since I'm not very familiar with pymysql, I'm not sure where the problem is. Could anyone help me solve this issue?
===2024/10/19 Update===
Hello everyone, Ive been dealing with other matters during this time, so I apologize for not responding earlier. Heres an update with the current Insert statement code, along with an image of the execution result.
import pymysql

conn_test = pymysql.connect(host='localhost', port=3306, user='root', passwd='exagger2024SQL', charset='utf8', db='pythonTest', autocommit=True)

with conn_test.cursor() as cursor:
    1
    sql_insert = """
        INSERT INTO pythonTest.Members (ID, Name, Height, Weight) VALUES
        (1, 'Tony', 170, 56),
        (2, 'Dawn', 167, 40),
        (3, 'Jack', 185, 83)
    """
    try:
        cursor.execute(sql_insert)

        conn_test.commit()
    except Exception as e:
        conn_test.rollback()

        print(e);

conn_test.close()


As you can see, this piece of code doesnt seem to show any errors, because if there were compilation errors, the 'try' and 'except' should have caught them, but they didnt.
At the same time, the SQL database still doesnt have any data like Tony and others.
Since Im new to this, Im feeling a bit lost. I really hope I can resolve this issue. In addition to continuing my research, I sincerely ask for your help. Thank you guys.

llm_zero_shot_body:
I'm experiencing an issue with my Python script that utilizes the Pygame library for game development. The script is designed to display a window with a yellow emoji character, but instead of displaying the character, it shows a distorted and pixelated image.

Here's the relevant code snippet:

```python
import pygame
import sys

# Initialize Pygame
pygame.init()

# Set up some constants
WIDTH, HEIGHT = 640, 480
WHITE = (255, 255, 255)

# Set up the display
screen = pygame.display.set_mode((WIDTH, HEIGHT))

# Set up the font
font = pygame.font.Font(None, 36)

# Set up the clock
clock = pygame.time.Clock()

# Game loop
while True:
    for event in pygame.event.get():
        if event.type == pygame.QUIT:
            pygame.quit()
            sys.exit()

    # Fill the screen with white
    screen.fill(WHITE)

    # Render the text
    text = font.render("Hello, World!", True, (0, 0, 0))
    screen.blit(text, (100, 100))

    # Update the display
    pygame.display.flip()

    # Cap the frame rate
    clock.tick(60)
```

The expected behavior is that the window should display the text "Hello, World!" in black font on a white background. However, the actual behavior is that the window displays a distorted and pixelated image of a yellow emoji character.

I've tried adjusting the font size, color, and position, but nothing seems to resolve the issue. I've also checked the Pygame documentation and searched online for similar issues, but I couldn't find any solutions.

I would appreciate any help in resolving this issue and getting the script to display the text correctly. Thank you for your time and assistance.

llm_cot_title: Python Code Error - "Program Files (x86)" Directory Not Found in Windows 10 Environment.
llm_cot_body:
I'm trying to use the `pytest` framework to write unit tests for my Python code, but I'm running into an issue with the `pytest.mark.parametrize` decorator. When I try to run my tests using the `pytest` command, I get an error message that says "TypeError: 'NoneType' object is not iterable". I've tried searching online for solutions, but I haven't found anything that works. I've also tried printing out the values of the variables involved in the test, but they seem to be correct. I'm using Python 3.8 and pytest 6.2.2. Has anyone else encountered this issue? Is there a known solution or workaround? 

Here is the code snippet that is causing the issue:

```python
import pytest

@pytest.mark.parametrize("input, expected", [
    ("hello", "world"),
    ("foo", "bar"),
])
def test_my_function(input, expected):
    assert my_function(input) == expected
```

I've tried changing the order of the parameters, using different types of inputs, and even commenting out the `parametrize` decorator, but nothing seems to work. I'm starting to think that it might be a bug in the `pytest` framework itself. Has anyone else experienced this issue? Any help would be greatly appreciated.

Here's the relevant code snippet:

```python
def test_string_equality():
    assert "hello" == "world"  # this will fail
    assert "hello" == "hello"  # this will pass

def test_string_equality_failed():
    def test():
        assert "hello" == "world"  # this will fail
        assert "hello" == "hello"  # this will pass
```

llm_cot_title: "AssertionError: assert 'hello' == 'world' failed"
llm_cot_body:
I'm trying to implement a feature in my web application using Python and the Flask framework. The goal is to handle user input and perform specific actions based on the input received. However, I'm encountering an issue where the application fails to process the input correctly, leading to unexpected behavior.

The error message I receive is "AssertionError: assert 'hello' == 'world'". This suggests that there's a mismatch between the expected and actual values. Upon reviewing my code, I realize that I've made an incorrect assumption about the user's input.

To troubleshoot this issue, I've tried several approaches:

1. **Checking the User Input**: I've added print statements to verify the value of the user's input. This helps me understand what the user is entering and how it's being processed by the application.
2. **Reviewing the Code Logic**: I've carefully reviewed the logic of my code to ensure that it accurately reflects the desired behavior. This involves checking the conditional statements and the actions taken based on the user's input.
3. **Consulting Documentation**: I've consulted the Flask documentation to ensure that I'm using the correct methods and functions to handle user input. This helps me identify any potential mistakes or areas for improvement.

Despite these efforts, I'm still struggling to resolve the issue. I believe that there might be a fundamental flaw in my approach or a misunderstanding of how Flask handles user input. I would appreciate any guidance or insights that could help me overcome this challenge.

Here's a simplified version of my code to illustrate the problem:

```python
from flask import Flask, request

app = Flask(__name__)

@app.route('/', methods=['POST'])
def handle_input():
    user_input = request.form['input']
    if user_input == 'hello':
        return 'world'
    else:
        return 'invalid input'

if __name__ == '__main__':
    app.run(debug=True)
```

In this example, I'm expecting the user to enter 'hello', but the application is not processing the input correctly. I'm hoping that someone can point out the mistake and provide a solution to this problem.

Title: Problem after updating to geoflutterfire_plus package
Title_Body:
<<Problem after updating to geoflutterfire_plus package>>
<<I use to have the package geoflutterfire2, I used this package to get the id of users that where in a certain distance from a specific location (latitude and longitude), my code was:
getSuppliersLocation(BuildContext context, int requestReach, String serviceCode,
    double lat, double long) async {
  final serviceRequest = Provider.of<CustomerRequest>(context, listen: false);
  final user = firebaseAuth.currentUser?.uid;
  final fcmToken = await firebaseMessaging.getToken();

  late Stream<List<DocumentSnapshot>> stream;
  late GeoFlutterFire geo;

  geo = GeoFlutterFire();
  final radius = requestReach / 1000;
  String field = 'location';

  String collectionRoute;
  productionStatus
      ? collectionRoute = 'supplier'
      : collectionRoute = 'Testsupplier';

  var collectionReference = firestore
      .collection(collectionRoute)
      .where(serviceCode, isEqualTo: true)
      .where('isActive', isEqualTo: true)
      .where('isVerified', isEqualTo: true);

  GeoFirePoint center = geo.point(latitude: lat, longitude: long);

  stream = geo
      .collection(collectionRef: collectionReference)
      .within(center: center, radius: radius, field: field, strictMode: true);

  controllerSuppliers = stream.listen((List<DocumentSnapshot> documentList) {
    List<String> ids = [];
    List<String> tokenIds = [];
    List<String> phoneNumbers = [];
    for (var item in documentList) {
      final data = item.data() as Map<String, dynamic>;
      if (data.containsKey('id') && data['id'] != user) {
        ids.add(data['id']);
      }
      if (data.containsKey('tokenId') && data['tokenId'] != fcmToken) {

I'm having trouble with a specific part of my code that's causing an error. The error message is pointing to this line: `if (i < 0) {`. It seems like the issue is with the condition `i < 0`, but I'm not sure why it's failing. I've tried changing the condition to `i <= 0` and `i >= 0`, but neither of those work. Can anyone help me understand what's going on here?

**Response:**

The issue here is likely due to the fact that `i` is not being initialized before the comparison. In C++, variables are not automatically initialized to zero, so if `i` is not explicitly set to a value before the comparison, it will contain garbage data, which can lead to unexpected behavior.

To fix this, you should initialize `i` to a valid value before the comparison. For example:

```c
int i = 0;
if (i < 0) {
    // code here
}
```

Alternatively, you can use a different data type that is guaranteed to be initialized to zero, such as `size_t`:

Title: How can I change the text using the new ContentChild signal API?
Title_Body:
<<How can I change the text using the new ContentChild signal API?>>
<<I'm trying to migrate my Angular component to use the new ContentChild signal API, but I'm encountering some TypeScript issues.
Here's my existing code using the traditional @ContentChild decorator:
// child-component.ts
import { Component, ContentChild, ElementRef, AfterContentInit } from '@angular/core';

@Component({
  selector: 'app-child',
  templateUrl: './child-component.html',
})
export class ChildComponent implements AfterContentInit {
  @ContentChild('headerTitle', { static: true }) headerTitleContent!: ElementRef; // Access projected title
  @ContentChild('headerSubtitle', { static: true }) headerSubtitleContent!: ElementRef; // Access projected subtitle
  @ContentChild('navbar') navTitle!: ElementRef; // Access navbar

  constructor() {
    console.log(this.headerTitleContent); // Access title element
  }

  ngAfterContentInit() {
    this.headerSubtitleContent.nativeElement.textContent = 'Enjoy a customized experience!';
  }
}

I want to achieve the same functionality using the new ContentChild signal API as follows:
import { Component } from '@angular/core';
import { contentChild, effect } from '@angular/core';

@Component({
  selector: 'app-child',
  templateUrl: './child-component.html',
})
export class ChildComponent {
  private headerTitleContent = contentChild<ElementRef<HTMLAnchorElement>>('headerTitle');
  private headerSubtitleContent = contentChild<ElementRef<HTMLAnchorElement>>('headerSubtitle');
  private navTitle = contentChild<ElementRef<HTMLElement>>('navbar');

  constructor() {
    console.log(this.headerTitleContent); // Access title element
    effect(() => {
      if (this.headerSubtitleContent()) {
        this.headerSubtitleContent().nativeElement.textContent = 'HI this is my name'; // Issue occurs here
      }
    });
  }
}

ISSUE
The left-hand side of an assignment expression may not be an optional property access.

llm_few_shot_title: "How to Remove Duplicate Rows in Excel?"**
llm_few_shot_combined:
<<"How to Remove Duplicate Rows in Excel?"**>>
<<**

I'm having trouble with a JavaScript function that's supposed to update a table with new data. The issue is that the table isn't updating correctly, and I'm getting an error message that says "Cannot read property 'length' of undefined" when I try to access the table's rows.

The relevant code snippet is:

```javascript
const table = document.getElementById('myTable');
const data = [...]; // new data to update the table

// update the table
table.rows.forEach((row) => {
  row.cells.forEach((cell) => {
    cell.textContent = data[cell.rowIndex];
  });
});
```

The error message is pointing to the line where I'm trying to access the `length` property of the `row` object. I've tried checking the `row` object in the debugger, and it seems to be undefined.

I've also tried using `table.rows.length` to get the number of rows in the table, but it's still returning `undefined`.

Can anyone help me figure out what's going on and how to fix this issue?

**Response:**

The issue here is that the `row` object is not defined in the `forEach` loop. The `forEach` method only iterates over the array of rows, but it doesn't provide a reference to the current row object.

To fix this, you can use the `map` method instead, which returns a new array with the transformed values. You can then use the `forEach` method on the resulting array to update the table cells.

Here's the corrected code:

```javascript
const table = document.getElementById('myTable');
const data = [...]; // new data to update the table

// update the table
table.rows.map((row) => {
  row.cells.forEach((cell) => {
    cell.textContent = data[cell.rowIndex];
  });
});
```

Alternatively, you can use the `for` loop to iterate over the rows and update the cells:

```javascript
const table = document.getElementById('myTable');
const data = [...]; // new data to update the table

// update the table
for (let i = 0; i < table.rows.length; i++) {
  const row = table.rows[i];
  row.cells.forEach((cell) => {
    cell.textContent = data[i];
  });
}
```

Either of these approaches should fix the issue and update the table correctly.>>

```cpp
#include <algorithm>

    int arr[] = {5, 2, 8, 3, 1, 6, 4};
```

```cpp
std::sort(arr, arr + 7);
```

Alternatively, you can also use the `using namespace std;` directive at the top of your file to bring the entire `std` namespace into scope, like this:

```cpp
using namespace std;

int main() {
    int arr[] = {5, 2, 8, 3, 1, 6, 4};
    sort(arr, arr + 7);
    return 0;
}
```

Either of these changes should fix the error and allow your code to compile and run correctly.>>

I'm having trouble with my code and I'm hoping someone can help me out. I'm trying to implement a feature that involves using the `std::sort` function, but I'm getting an error message that says "no matching function for call to 'std::sort'". I've included the relevant code snippet below:

```cpp
#include <algorithm>
#include <vector>

int main() {
    std::vector<int> myVector = {3, 6, 1, 8, 2, 4};
    std::sort(myVector.begin(), myVector.end());
    return 0;
}
```

The error message is pointing to the line where I call `std::sort`, and I'm not sure what's going wrong. I've tried searching online for similar issues, but I haven't been able to find a solution. Can anyone help me figure out what's going on?

**Response:**

The issue here is that the `std::sort` function is not being found because the `algorithm` header file is not being included. The `std::sort` function is declared in the `algorithm` header file, which is not included in the code snippet.

To fix this issue, you need to add the following line at the top of your code:

```cpp
#include <algorithm>
```

This will allow the compiler to find the `std::sort` function and compile the code successfully.

Additionally, you can also use the `std::sort` function with the `std::vector` class, which is a part of the C++ Standard Library. You can use the `std::sort` function like this:

```cpp
#include <algorithm>
#include <vector>

int main() {
    std::vector<int> myVector = {3, 6, 1, 8, 2, 4};
    std::sort(myVector.begin(), myVector.end());
    return 0;
}
```

This will sort the elements of the `myVector` in ascending order.>>

Title: Fullcalendar Angular. How is the eventContent Angular template actually rendered in FullCalendar?
Body:
Fullcalendar supports an eventContent and numerous other callbacks letting us to define custom templates for event UI and etc...
There is a wrapper library called @fullcalendar/angular, it provides a way to define custom event template in angular style and it renders into the correct spot the calendar.
<full-calendar [options]="calendarOptions()">
  <ng-template #eventContent let-arg>
    I am an event with {{ binding }} and {{ arg.event.title }}
  </ng-template>
</full-calendar>

My question: How actually this library makes it work? Fullcalendar in a nutshell is just a javascript library and I expect there is somewhere eventContent callback is called and this library does a trick by taking the template and creating a DOM element out of it. Can you tell me what technique is used for that? I can rephrase a question: how to dynamically generate a DOM Element, a template of which is managed by Angular. I even fine if change detection will not work automatically (it probably won't).
I pulled a source repo and it's content is very strange to me. I see how the eventContent is read from @contentChildren but nothing happens with it after.

llm_few_shot_title: "How to fix 'No such file or directory' error in Python script?"**
llm_few_shot_body:
I am having trouble with my code and I need some help. I am trying to create a function that will take a list of numbers and return the sum of all the numbers in the list. However, when I run the function, I get an error message that says "TypeError: unsupported operand type(s) for +: 'int' and 'str'". I have attached a screenshot of my code and the error message.

The most important part of the error message is the "TypeError: unsupported operand type(s) for +: 'int' and 'str'" part. This tells me that there is a problem with the data type of one of the variables in my function.

I have tried to debug my code, but I am not sure what is causing the error. I have checked that all of the variables are of the correct data type, but I am still getting the error.

Can someone please help me figure out what is going on and how to fix the error?

Response:

The issue you are experiencing is due to the fact that your list contains both integers and strings. When you try to add an integer and a string together, Python throws a TypeError because it doesn't know how to perform the operation.

To fix this issue, you need to make sure that all of the elements in your list are of the same data type. You can do this by using a list comprehension to filter out any non-integer elements from your list.

Here is an example of how you can do this:

```python
def sum_numbers(numbers):
    return sum(num for num in numbers if isinstance(num, int))

numbers = [1, 2, '3', 4, 'five']
print(sum_numbers(numbers))  # Output: 6
```

In this example, the list comprehension `num for num in numbers if isinstance(num, int)` filters out any non-integer elements from the list, leaving only the integers. The `sum` function then adds up the remaining integers.

Alternatively, you can use a try-except block to catch the TypeError and handle it accordingly. For example:

```python
def sum_numbers(numbers):
    try:
        return sum(numbers)
    except TypeError:
        return "Error: List contains non-integer elements"

numbers = [1, 2, '3', 4, 'five']
print(sum_numbers(numbers))  # Output: Error: List contains non-integer elements
```

In this example, the try block attempts to add up all of the elements in the list. If a TypeError is raised, the except block catches it and returns an error message.

llm_cot_combined:
<<Error in Python Code: Unhandled Exception in IDE**>>
<<I'm experiencing an issue with my code in the Eclipse IDE, where I'm encountering a "NullPointerException" error when trying to access a method of an object that I believe should be initialized. The error message is not providing much insight into the cause of the problem.

The relevant code snippet is as follows:

```java
public class MyClass {
    private MyObject myObject;

    public MyClass() {
        myObject = new MyObject();
    }

    public void myMethod() {
        myObject.doSomething(); // This line throws the NullPointerException
    }
}

public class MyObject {
    public void doSomething() {
        System.out.println("Doing something...");
    }
}
```

I've tried debugging the code by setting breakpoints and inspecting the values of variables, but I haven't been able to identify the root cause of the issue. I've also reviewed the documentation for the Eclipse IDE and the Java language, but I haven't found any relevant information that would help me resolve this problem.

I've attempted to troubleshoot the issue by checking the initialization of the `myObject` variable, but it appears to be properly initialized in the constructor of the `MyClass` class. I've also tried printing out the value of `myObject` before calling the `doSomething()` method, but it prints out `null`.

I would appreciate any help in identifying the cause of this issue and finding a solution. Is there something obvious that I'm missing? Are there any additional troubleshooting steps that I can take? 

I've included the entire stacktrace below for reference:

```
Exception in thread "main" java.lang.NullPointerException
    at MyClass.myMethod(MyClass.java:10)
    at Main.main(Main.java:5)
```

Thank you for your time and assistance.>>

Title: electron-updater stops on checking for update
Body:
I'm using electron-updater 6.3.
It works fine for auto updates on Windows and Mac but I have this one Mac user who is sometimes have issues. Specifically when there are no updates available.
In that case I can see from logging out that electron-updater only get to this point (see attached screenshot).
It only gets to "Checking for update". It never reaches the "update-not-available" event.
I don't get any errors either.
I'm using Github releases. I know I'm not giving much information here but does anyone know common reasons why this would happen?

llm_zero_shot_title: Cannot check for updates: $(e.stack || e.toString())
llm_zero_shot_combined:
<<Cannot check for updates: $(e.stack || e.toString())>>
<<I'm experiencing an issue with my code where the `checkForUpdatesPromise` function is not returning the expected result. The function is supposed to check for updates and return a promise that resolves with the result of the update check. However, when I call the function, it returns `undefined` instead of the expected promise.

Here's the relevant code snippet:

```javascript
const checkForUpdatesPromise = () => {
  return Promise.resolve(null);
};

const checkForUpdates = async () => {
  const result = await checkForUpdatesPromise();
  console.log(result); // Output: undefined
};
```

As you can see, the `checkForUpdatesPromise` function returns a promise that resolves with `null`. However, when I call the function using `await`, it returns `undefined` instead of the expected `null`.

I've tried debugging the issue by adding console logs and using the debugger, but I couldn't find any clues as to why this is happening. I've also checked the documentation for the `Promise.resolve` method, but it seems to be working as expected.

I'm using Node.js version 14.17.0 and the latest version of the `promise` package. I've also tried running the code in different environments, but the issue persists.

Has anyone else encountered this issue? Any help or guidance would be greatly appreciated.

**Expected Behavior:**

* The `checkForUpdatesPromise` function should return a promise that resolves with the result of the update check.
* The `checkForUpdates` function should log the result of the update check to the console.

**Actual Behavior:**

* The `checkForUpdatesPromise` function returns `undefined` instead of the expected promise.
* The `checkForUpdates` function logs `undefined` to the console instead of the expected result.

**Relevant Code:**

```javascript
const checkForUpdatesPromise = () => {
  return Promise.resolve(null);
};

const checkForUpdates = async () => {
  const result = await checkForUpdatesPromise();
  console.log(result); // Output: undefined
};
```

**Environment:**

* Node.js version: 14.17.0
* `promise` package version: latest
* Operating System: macOS High Sierra
* IDE: Visual Studio Code

**Additional Information:**

* I've tried running the code in different environments, but the issue persists.
* I've checked the documentation for the `Promise.resolve` method, but it seems to be working as expected.>>

<<Error in Electron Updater: "Cannot check for updates: $(e.stack || e.toString())">>
<<I'm trying to use the `checkForUpdates` function from the `electron-builder` package to check for updates in my Electron application. However, when I run the code, I get an error message saying "Cannot check for updates: $(n.stack || e.toString())". I've tried searching for solutions online, but I couldn't find anything that works. I'm using Electron version 13.1.8 and electron-builder version 22.10.0. Here's my code:

```javascript
const { checkForUpdates } = require('electron-builder');

checkForUpdates().then((updateInfo) => {
  if (updateInfo) {
    console.log('Update available:', updateInfo);
  } else {
    console.log('No update available');
  }
}).catch((error) => {
  console.error('Error checking for updates:', error);
});
```

I've also tried using the `checkForUpdatesPromise` function, but it gives me the same error:

```javascript
const { checkForUpdatesPromise } = require('electron-builder');

checkForUpdatesPromise().then((updateInfo) => {
  if (updateInfo) {
    console.log('Update available:', updateInfo);
  } else {
    console.log('No update available');
  }
}).catch((error) => {
  console.error('Error checking for updates:', error);
});
```

I've checked the Electron documentation and the electron-builder documentation, but I couldn't find any information on how to fix this issue. I've also tried updating my Electron version and electron-builder version, but it didn't make a difference. Can someone please help me figure out what's going on and how to fix it?>>

Title: OpenAPI generates AdditionalProperties field twice
Body:
I am generating Swagger client via the OpenAPI but getting an error for additionalProperties as it was defined twice.
The json schema was generated from FastEndpoints project, I tried to add schema filter configuration to disallow the AdditionalPropertiesAllowed - yet no luck.
I'm trying to understand how do we configure the additionalProperties to appear only once in the json schema:

UPDATE:
The issue that I encountered on the generated json schema with additionalProperties defined twice is when I try to generate a CSharpClient through json the client throws an error with
additionalProperties defined twice in the model.

llm_zero_shot_title: ** "TypeError: 'NoneType' object is not subscriptable" when accessing nested dictionary values in Python.
llm_zero_shot_body:
I'm experiencing an issue with my code where the "additionalProperties" property is not being recognized as a valid property in my JSON schema. 

Here's a screenshot of the error:

[Insert Screenshot]

The relevant code snippet is as follows:

```json
{
  "$schema": "http://json-schema.org/draft-07/schema#",
  "type": "object",
  "properties": {
    "additionalProperties": {
      "type": "object",
      "nullable": true,
      "additionalProperties": {}
    }
  }
}
```

I expect the "additionalProperties" property to be recognized as a valid property in my JSON schema, allowing me to define additional properties for my object. However, the error message indicates that it is not a valid property. 

I've tried searching for similar issues, but couldn't find any relevant solutions. I'd appreciate any help in resolving this issue. 

Please note that I'm using the draft-07 version of the JSON schema. 

Thanks in advance for your assistance. 

**UPDATE**: I've tried updating the JSON schema to the latest version (draft-2020-12), but the issue persists. 

**UPDATE 2**: I've also tried removing the "nullable" property, but it doesn't make a difference. 

**UPDATE 3**: I've tried using a different IDE, but the issue is still present. 

I'm starting to think that this might be a bug in the JSON schema validation library I'm using. Has anyone else encountered this issue? 

**UPDATE 4**: I've tried using a different JSON schema validation library, and the issue is resolved. It seems that the issue was specific to the library I was using. 

Thanks to everyone who helped me troubleshoot this issue. I'll make sure to update my question with the solution once I've confirmed it. 

**SOLUTION**: The issue was resolved by switching to a different JSON schema validation library. The library I was using had a bug that caused the "additionalProperties" property to be unrecognized. 

I hope this helps anyone else who encounters this issue. Thanks again for your assistance.

Title: Get VSCode to recognize aliases
Title_Body:
<<Get VSCode to recognize aliases>>
<<Ok, so I built an app with Vite and React. I added some aliases to make things easier to read, it works, but VSC is dumb and doesn't pick up on the aliases, which also means it has trouble inferring types and so on.
It's especially dumb since, for instance, @store gets highlighted as being a problem, but @store/index works perfectly. What am I doing wrong here?!
/* vite.config.ts */

import { defineConfig } from "vite";
import react from "@vitejs/plugin-react";
import path from "path";

export default defineConfig({
  plugins: [react()],

  resolve: {
    alias: {
      "@": path.resolve(__dirname, "./src"),
      "@assets": path.resolve(__dirname, "./src/assets"),
      "@core": path.resolve(__dirname, "./src/core"),
      "@store": path.resolve(__dirname, "./src/core/store"),
      "@user": path.resolve(__dirname, "./src/user"),
    },
  },
});

/* tsconfig.app.json */ 

{
  "compilerOptions": {
    "target": "ES2020",
    "useDefineForClassFields": true,
    "lib": ["ES2020", "DOM", "DOM.Iterable"],
    "module": "ESNext",
    "skipLibCheck": true,

    /* Bundler mode */
    "moduleResolution": "bundler",
    "allowImportingTsExtensions": true,
    "isolatedModules": true,
    "moduleDetection": "force",
    "noEmit": true,
    "jsx": "react-jsx",

    /* Linting */
    "strict": true,
    "noUnusedLocals": true,
    "noUnusedParameters": true,
    "noFallthroughCasesInSwitch": true,

    "baseUrl": "./src",
    "paths": {
      "@/*": ["*"],
      "@assets/*": ["assets/*"],
      "@core/*": ["core/*"],
      "@store/*": ["core/store/*"],
      "@user/*": ["user/*"]
    }
  },
  "include": ["src/**/*"]
}

Again, it works, it does compile and run, and I didn't even have to add the aliases to the tsconfig file - which makes sense, I hate having to add it to 2 separate places anyway. But VSCode is still being dumb...

>>

Title: LangGraph Error - Invalid Tool Calls when using AzureChatOpenAI
Body:
I'm following the LangGraph tutorial (from LangGraph) and I'm getting an error when switching from "ChatOpenAI" to "AzureChatOpenAI". This is the code example from the website:
from langchain_openai import AzureChatOpenAI
from dotenv import find_dotenv, load_dotenv
import os

from langgraph.graph import MessagesState
from langchain_core.messages import HumanMessage, SystemMessage

from langgraph.graph import START, StateGraph
from langgraph.prebuilt import tools_condition
from langgraph.prebuilt import ToolNode
from IPython.display import Image, display

load_dotenv(find_dotenv(), override=True)
  

This is the only change I've done, I've modified how to initialize the LLM (I am using AzureChatOpen AI) instead of ChatOpenAI 4o model.
llm = AzureChatOpenAI(
                openai_api_version=os.getenv("OPENAI_API_VERSION"),
                azure_deployment=os.getenv("DEPLOYMENT_NAME"),
                azure_endpoint=os.getenv("AZURE_OPENAI_ENDPOINT"), 
                temperature=0,
            )

Then the remain code:
def multiply(a: int, b: int) -> int:
    """Multiply a and b.

    Args:
        a: first int
        b: second int
    """
    return a * b

def add(a: int, b: int) -> int:
    """Adds a and b.

    Args:
        a: first int
        b: second int
    """
    return a + b
      

tools = [add, multiply]

llm_with_tools = llm.bind_tools(tools)


sys_msg = SystemMessage(content="You are a helpful assistant tasked with performing arithmetic on a set of inputs.")

def assistant(state: MessagesState):
   return {"messages": [llm_with_tools.invoke([sys_msg] + state["messages"])]}

# Graph
builder = StateGraph(MessagesState)

builder.add_node("assistant", assistant)
builder.add_node("tools", ToolNode(tools))

builder.add_edge(START, "assistant")
builder.add_conditional_edges(
    "assistant",
    tools_condition,
)
builder.add_edge("tools", "assistant")
react_graph = builder.compile()

And this is the call (how to reproduce the error):
messages = [HumanMessage(content="Add 3 and 4. Multiply the output by 2. Using the local tool")]

messages = react_graph.invoke({"messages": messages})

print the result:
for m in messages['messages']:
    m.pretty_print()

And this is the error I get:

**

I'm experiencing an issue with my Python script that's causing it to crash. The error message I'm getting is:

`TypeError: 'NoneType' object is not subscriptable`

This error is occurring when I try to access a specific element in a list using indexing. I've checked the list and it's not empty, but for some reason, the script is trying to access an element that doesn't exist.

I've tried printing out the list before trying to access the element, and it looks fine. I've also tried using the `try-except` block to catch the error, but it's not helping.

Here's the relevant code snippet:

```python
my_list = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]
print(my_list[5])  # This line is causing the error
```

I'm not sure what's going on or how to fix it. Can anyone help me out?

**Response:**

The issue here is that you're trying to access an element in the list that doesn't exist. In Python, list indices start at 0, so the last valid index for your list `my_list` is 4. When you try to access `my_list[5]`, Python throws a `TypeError` because there is no element at that index.

To fix this, you can either change the index to a valid one or add more elements to the list. Here's an updated version of your code:

```python
my_list = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6]  # Add another element to the list
print(my_list[5])  # This should work now
```

Alternatively, you can use the `try-except` block to catch the error and handle it accordingly:

```python
my_list = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]
try:
    print(my_list[5])
except IndexError:
    print("Error: Index out of range")
```

This way, if the index is out of range, the script will print "Error: Index out of range" instead of crashing.

I'm trying to implement a custom authentication system using Django's built-in authentication framework. However, when I attempt to log in with a valid username and password, I receive a "NoneType" error. The error message indicates that the `user` object is `None`, which suggests that the authentication process is not correctly retrieving the user instance.

I've reviewed the Django documentation and ensured that my `User` model is properly defined and registered in the `AUTH_USER_MODEL` setting. I've also verified that the `username` and `password` fields are correctly populated in the `User` model.

To troubleshoot this issue, I've tried printing the `user` object before and after the authentication attempt to see if it's being correctly retrieved. However, the `user` object remains `None` even after a successful authentication attempt.

Here's the relevant code snippet:
```python
from django.contrib.auth import authenticate, login
from django.http import HttpResponse

def login_view(request):
    username = request.POST['username']
    password = request.POST['password']
    user = authenticate(request, username=username, password=password)
    if user is not None:
        login(request, user)
        return HttpResponse('Login successful!')
    else:
        return HttpResponse('Invalid username or password.')
```
I've also checked the Django documentation for any known issues or edge cases related to custom authentication, but I couldn't find any relevant information.

I would appreciate any guidance on how to resolve this issue and correctly implement custom authentication in Django.

Title: Azure DevOps. Can't trigger a pipeline in Repo A when a commit is done in repo B
Body:
Im using Version Dev17.M153.5 (TFS), and I have two repositories: my source code is hosted in Repo B, and my pipelines are hosted in Repo A to keep responsibilities separated.
My goal is for the pipeline in Repo A to automatically run whenever a commit is pushed to Repo B. Below is my current setup:
# MY MAIN PIPELINE IN REPO A:
trigger: none
resources:
  repositories:
    - repository: RepoB
      type: git
      name: Project/RepoB
      ref: develop
      trigger:
        branches:
          include:
            - develop
            - master

pool:
  name: 'Test'

variables:
  REPO_URL: 'https://tfs.company.com/company/Project/_git/RepoB'

steps:
  - task: PowerShell@2
    displayName: 'Configurar encabezado GIT_AUTH_HEADER con PAT'
    inputs:
      targetType: 'inline'
      script: |
        # Crear el encabezado de autenticacin en formato Base64
        $headerValue = "Authorization: Basic " + [Convert]::ToBase64String([System.Text.Encoding]::UTF8.GetBytes(":" + $env:PAT))

        git -c http.extraheader="$headerValue" clone $(REPO_URL)
    env:
      PAT: $(PAT)  # El PAT como variable de entorno secreta

    #Templates
  - ${{ if eq(variables['Build.SourceBranch'], 'refs/heads/master') }}:
    - template: pipeline-master.yml

  - ${{ if eq(variables['Build.SourceBranch'], 'refs/heads/develop') }}:
    - template: pipeline-develop.yml

The Issue:
This pipeline does not trigger automatically when a commit is pushed to Repo B on either develop or master. I cannot use checkout because it only accepts self or none. However, Repo B is successfully cloned, and the pipeline runs fine if I trigger it manually
Additional Considerations:

Build services have "Read and Contribute" permissions set to "Allow" in both repositories.
Both Repo A and Repo B are part of the same project.
The Personal Access Token (PAT) is correctly configured, and the pipeline passes when executed manually.


Question:
Why is the pipeline not triggering automatically, and how can I ensure it runs whenever a commit is pushed to Repo B?
Update
I have read many posts warning about compiling the YAML file in the default branch. I am compiling it in master, which is my default branch, and still doesn't work
Many thanks in advance!
Title_Body:
<<Azure DevOps. Can't trigger a pipeline in Repo A when a commit is done in repo B>>
<<Im using Version Dev17.M153.5 (TFS), and I have two repositories: my source code is hosted in Repo B, and my pipelines are hosted in Repo A to keep responsibilities separated.
My goal is for the pipeline in Repo A to automatically run whenever a commit is pushed to Repo B. Below is my current setup:
# MY MAIN PIPELINE IN REPO A:
trigger: none
resources:
  repositories:
    - repository: RepoB
      type: git
      name: Project/RepoB
      ref: develop
      trigger:
        branches:
          include:
            - develop
            - master

pool:
  name: 'Test'

variables:
  REPO_URL: 'https://tfs.company.com/company/Project/_git/RepoB'

steps:
  - task: PowerShell@2
    displayName: 'Configurar encabezado GIT_AUTH_HEADER con PAT'
    inputs:
      targetType: 'inline'
      script: |
        # Crear el encabezado de autenticacin en formato Base64
        $headerValue = "Authorization: Basic " + [Convert]::ToBase64String([System.Text.Encoding]::UTF8.GetBytes(":" + $env:PAT))

        git -c http.extraheader="$headerValue" clone $(REPO_URL)
    env:
      PAT: $(PAT)  # El PAT como variable de entorno secreta

    #Templates
  - ${{ if eq(variables['Build.SourceBranch'], 'refs/heads/master') }}:
    - template: pipeline-master.yml

  - ${{ if eq(variables['Build.SourceBranch'], 'refs/heads/develop') }}:
    - template: pipeline-develop.yml

The Issue:
This pipeline does not trigger automatically when a commit is pushed to Repo B on either develop or master. I cannot use checkout because it only accepts self or none. However, Repo B is successfully cloned, and the pipeline runs fine if I trigger it manually
Additional Considerations:

Build services have "Read and Contribute" permissions set to "Allow" in both repositories.
Both Repo A and Repo B are part of the same project.
The Personal Access Token (PAT) is correctly configured, and the pipeline passes when executed manually.


Question:
Why is the pipeline not triggering automatically, and how can I ensure it runs whenever a commit is pushed to Repo B?
Update
I have read many posts warning about compiling the YAML file in the default branch. I am compiling it in master, which is my default branch, and still doesn't work
Many thanks in advance!
>>

llm_few_shot_title: "How to Remove Duplicate Rows in Excel?"**
llm_few_shot_body:
**

I am experiencing an issue with my code, and I would appreciate any assistance in resolving it. The error message I am encountering is:

"Error: Cannot convert type 'System.String' to 'System.Int32'."

This error is occurring in the following line of code:

`int x = (int)myString;`

The most important part of this error message is the type mismatch between the expected type 'System.Int32' and the actual type 'System.String'. I have tried to cast the string to an integer, but it is not working as expected.

I have included a screenshot of the code and the error message below:

[Insert Screenshot]

I am using C# and Visual Studio 2019. I have searched online for solutions, but I could not find anything that matches my specific issue. I would greatly appreciate any help or guidance you can provide in resolving this issue.

**Response:**

The issue you are experiencing is due to the fact that you are trying to cast a string to an integer. In C#, strings are objects, and integers are value types. You cannot directly cast a string to an integer.

To resolve this issue, you need to parse the string to an integer. You can use the `int.Parse()` method to do this:

`int x = int.Parse(myString);`

Alternatively, you can use the `int.TryParse()` method to handle any potential errors:

`if (int.TryParse(myString, out int x)) { ... }`

Make sure to handle any potential errors that may occur during the parsing process.

**Additional Information:**

* Make sure that the string you are trying to parse is in the correct format (e.g., "123" for an integer).
* If you are using a culture that uses commas as decimal separators, you may need to use the `CultureInfo.InvariantCulture` parameter when parsing the string.

I hope this helps resolve your issue. If you have any further questions or need additional assistance, please let me know.

Title: how to use formatjs plugin in rspack's swc loader
Title_Body:
<<how to use formatjs plugin in rspack's swc loader>>
<<Recently I migrated a application from webpack to rspack.
Previously we were using babel-loader to transpile. Now we decided to use rspack's builtin swc-loader.
We are using formatjs for intl support.
here is the swc-loader configuration for rspack
const js = {
  test: /\.js(x)?$/,
  exclude: [
    /node_modules/,
    path.join(config.root, config.paths.src, 'web', 'javascripts/vendors/'),
  ],
  loader: 'builtin:swc-loader',
  options: {
    jsc: {
      parser: {
        syntax: 'ecmascript',
        jsx: true,
      },
      transform: {
        react: {
          runtime: 'automatic',
          development: config.env === 'production',
          refresh: config.env === 'production',
        },
      },
      experimental: {
        plugins: [
          [
            '@formatjs/swc-plugin',
            {
              overrideIdFn: '[sha512:contenthash:base64:6]',
              ast: true,
            },
          ],
        ],
      },
    },
    type: 'javascript/auto',
    env: {
      targets: 'Chrome >= 48',
    },
  },
};

And here is the build error I am facing after using the formatjs plugin:

For reference, here is the explanation for the formatjs plugin
https://formatjs.io/docs/tooling/swc-plugin/
How can I use the formatjs plugin with rspack and swc loader?
>>

```python
import binascii

def convert_to_binary(input_string):
    try:
        binary_data = binascii.unhexlify(input_string)
        return binary_data

        print(f"Error when converting wat: {e}")
```

I am experiencing an issue with my code where it is not correctly handling the conversion of a string to an integer. The error message I am receiving is "Cannot implicitly convert type 'string' to 'int'". I have tried using the `int.Parse()` method, but it is not working as expected.

The code snippet that is causing the issue is:

```csharp
string input = "123";
int result = int.Parse(input);
```

I have also tried using the `Convert.ToInt32()` method, but it is still not working.

I am using C# and Visual Studio 2019. I have checked the documentation and it seems that the `int.Parse()` method should work for converting a string to an integer.

Can anyone help me understand why this is not working and provide a solution?

**Response:**

The issue you are experiencing is due to the fact that the `int.Parse()` method is trying to parse a string that contains non-numeric characters. The `int.Parse()` method only works with strings that contain numeric characters.

To fix this issue, you can use the `int.TryParse()` method instead, which returns a boolean value indicating whether the conversion was successful. If the conversion is successful, you can then assign the result to an integer variable.

Here is an example of how you can modify your code to use `int.TryParse()`:

```csharp
string input = "123";
if (int.TryParse(input, out int result))
{
    Console.WriteLine(result);
}
else
{
    Console.WriteLine("Invalid input");
}
```

This code will check if the input string can be parsed as an integer, and if so, it will print the result. If the input string cannot be parsed as an integer, it will print "Invalid input".

Alternatively, you can use the `int.Parse()` method with a try-catch block to catch any exceptions that may be thrown:

```csharp
string input = "123";
try
{
    int result = int.Parse(input);
    Console.WriteLine(result);
}
catch (FormatException)
{
    Console.WriteLine("Invalid input");
}
```

This code will attempt to parse the input string as an integer, and if an exception is thrown, it will catch the exception and print "Invalid input".>>

`TypeError: expected str, bytes or os.PathLike object, not int`

This error is happening when I try to read the CSV file using the `pandas.read_csv()` function. I've checked the file and it's in the correct format, so I'm not sure what's causing the issue.

Here's the relevant code snippet:

```
import pandas as pd

# Read the CSV file
df = pd.read_csv('data.csv')
```

I've tried searching online for similar issues, but I couldn't find a solution that works for me. I'm using Python 3.9 and the latest version of pandas. Can anyone help me figure out what's going on?

**Response:**

The issue you're experiencing is likely due to the fact that the `read_csv()` function is expecting a string or bytes-like object as the file path, but you're passing an integer value instead.

To fix this, you need to make sure that the file path is a string. You can do this by wrapping the file path in quotes, like this:

```
df = pd.read_csv('data.csv')
```

Alternatively, you can use the `os.path.join()` function to join the directory path with the file name, like this:

```
import os

file_path = os.path.join('data', 'data.csv')
df = pd.read_csv(file_path)
```

This will ensure that the file path is a string, and the `read_csv()` function should work correctly.

```
import pandas as pd
```
